GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
H 2
HOUSE BILL 59
Committee Substitute Favorable 6/25/25
Short Title: Modify Homestead Exclusions. (Public)
Sponsors:
Referred to:
February 6, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO MODIFY THE INCOME ELIGIBILITY LIMIT FOR THE ELDERLY OR
3 DISABLED PROPERTY TAX HOMESTEAD EXCLUSION FOR MARRIED COUPLES,
4 TO ELIMINATE THE DEFERRED TAX LIABILITY UNDER THE PROPERTY TAX
5 HOMESTEAD CIRCUIT BREAKER, AND TO EXPAND THE PROPERTY TAX
6 HOMESTEAD CIRCUIT BREAKER BY PROVIDING AN ALTERNATE MEANS TO
7 QUALIFY BASED ON AREA MEDIAN INCOME.
8 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
9 SECTION 1.(a) G.S. 105-277.1 is amended by adding a new subsection to read:
10 "(a3) Spousal Income Limitation. – Married applicants residing with their spouses may
11 qualify for the property tax homestead exclusion provided in this section if their income does not
12 exceed one hundred fifteen percent (115%) of the income eligibility limit determined under
13 subsection (a2) of this section."
14 SECTION 1.(b) G.S. 105-277.1B reads as rewritten:
15 "§ 105-277.1B. Property tax homestead circuit breaker.
16 (a) Classification. – A permanent residence owned and occupied by a qualifying owner
17 is designated a special class of property under Article V, Section 2(2) of the North Carolina
18 Constitution and is taxable in accordance with this section.
19 (b) Definitions. – The definitions provided in G.S. 105-277.1 apply to this section.
20 (c) Income Eligibility Limit. – The income eligibility limit provided in
21 G.S. 105-277.1(a2) applies to this section.
22 (c1) AMI Limit. – Seventy percent (70%) of the area median income for a household of
23 two persons in the county in which the property is located, as determined by the most recent
24 figure reported by the United States Department of Housing and Urban Development as of
25 January 1 preceding the taxable year for which the benefit is claimed.
26 (d) Qualifying Owner. – For the purpose of qualifying for the property tax homestead
27 circuit breaker under this section, a qualifying owner is an owner who meets all of the following
28 requirements as of January 1 preceding the taxable year for which the benefit is claimed:
29 (1) The owner has an income for the preceding calendar year of not more than
30 one hundred fifty percent (150%) of the income eligibility limit specified
31 maximum amount authorized in subsection (c) subsection (f) or (f1) of this
32 section.section, as applicable.
33 (2) The owner has owned and occupied the property as a permanent residence for
34 at least five consecutive years and has occupied the property as a permanent
35 residence for at least five years.the required amount of time under subsection
36 (f) or (f1) of this section, as applicable.
