General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (3) The owner is at least 65 years of age or totally and permanently disabled.
2 (4) The owner is a North Carolina resident.
3 (e) Multiple Owners. – A permanent residence owned and occupied by husband and wife
4 is entitled to the full benefit of the property tax homestead circuit breaker notwithstanding that
5 only one of them meets the length of occupancy and ownership requirements and the age or
6 disability requirement of this section. When a permanent residence is owned and occupied by
7 two or more persons other than husband and wife, no property tax homestead circuit breaker is
8 allowed unless all of the owners qualify and elect to defer taxes under this section.
9 (f) General Tax Limitation. – A qualifying owner may defer that has owned the property
10 as a permanent residence for at least five consecutive years and has occupied the property as a
11 permanent residence for at least five years is relieved of the portion of the principal amount of
12 tax that is imposed for the current tax year on his or her permanent residence and exceeds the
13 percentage of the qualifying owner's income set out in the table in this subsection. If a permanent
14 residence is subject to tax by more than one taxing unit and the total tax liability exceeds the tax
15 limit imposed by this section, then both the taxes due under this section and the taxes deferred
16 under this section must be apportioned among the taxing units based upon the ratio each taxing
17 unit's tax rate bears to the total tax rate of all units.
18 Income Over Income Up To Percentage
19 -0- Income Eligibility Limit 4.0%
20 Income Eligibility Limit 150% of Income Eligibility Limit 5.0%
21 (f1) Alternate Tax Limitation. – A qualifying owner that has owned the property as a
22 permanent residence for at least 10 consecutive years and has occupied the property as a
23 permanent residence for at least 10 years is relieved of the portion of the principal amount of tax
24 that is imposed for the current tax year on his or her permanent residence and exceeds the
25 percentage of the qualifying owner's income set out in the table in this subsection. If a permanent
26 residence is subject to tax by more than one taxing unit and the total tax liability exceeds the tax
27 limit imposed by this section, then the taxes due under this section must be apportioned among
28 the taxing units based upon the ratio each taxing unit's tax rate bears to the total tax rate of all
29 units. If the AMI Limit is less than or equal to one hundred fifty percent (150%) of the Income
30 Eligibility Limit, a qualifying owner shall receive the benefit under subsection (f) of this section.
31 Income Over Income Up To Percentage
32 150% of Income Eligibility Limit AMI Limit 6.0%
33 (g) Temporary Absence. – An otherwise qualifying owner does not lose the benefit of
34 this circuit breaker because of a temporary absence from his or her permanent residence for
35 reasons of health, or because of an extended absence while confined to a rest home or nursing
36 home, so long as the residence is unoccupied or occupied by the owner's spouse or other
37 dependent.
38 (h) Deferred Taxes. – The difference between the taxes due under this section and the
39 taxes that would have been payable in the absence of this section are a lien on the real property
40 of the taxpayer as provided in G.S. 105-355(a). The difference in taxes must be carried forward
41 in the records of each taxing unit as deferred taxes. The deferred taxes for the preceding three
42 fiscal years are due and payable in accordance with G.S. 105-277.1F when the property loses its
43 eligibility for deferral as a result of a disqualifying event described in subsection (i) of this
44 section. On or before September 1 of each year, the collector must send to the mailing address of
45 a residence on which taxes have been deferred a notice stating the amount of deferred taxes and
46 interest that would be due and payable upon the occurrence of a disqualifying event.
47 (i) Disqualifying Events. – A property receiving the benefit under this section loses its
48 eligibility for the benefit as a result of a disqualifying event. The tax for the fiscal year that begins
49 in the calendar year in which the disqualifying event occurs is computed as if the property had
50 not been classified for the property tax benefit under this section for that year. Each of the
51 following constitutes a disqualifying event:
Page 2 House Bill 59-Second Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (1) The owner transfers the residence. Transfer of the residence is not a
2 disqualifying event if (i) the owner transfers the residence to a co-owner of
3 the residence or, as part of a divorce proceeding, to his or her spouse and (ii)
4 that individual occupies or continues to occupy the property as his or her
5 permanent residence.
6 (2) The owner dies. Death of the owner is not a disqualifying event if (i) the
7 owner's share passes to a co-owner of the residence or to his or her spouse and
8 (ii) that individual occupies or continues to occupy the property as his or her
9 permanent residence.
10 (3) The owner ceases to use the property as a permanent residence.
11 (j) Gap in Deferral. – If an owner of a residence on which taxes have been deferred under
12 this section is not eligible for continued deferral for a tax year, the deferred taxes are carried
13 forward and are not due and payable until a disqualifying event occurs. If the owner of the
14 residence qualifies for deferral after one or more years in which he or she did not qualify for
15 deferral and a disqualifying event occurs, the years in which the owner did not qualify are
16 disregarded in determining the preceding three years for which the deferred taxes are due and
17 payable.
18 (k) Repealed by Session Laws 2008-35, s. 1.2, effective July 1, 2008.
19 (l) Creditor Limitations. – A mortgagee or trustee that elects to pay any tax deferred by
20 the owner of a residence subject to a mortgage or deed of trust does not acquire a right to foreclose
21 as a result of the election. Except for requirements dictated by federal law or regulation, any
22 provision in a mortgage, deed of trust, or other agreement that prohibits the owner from deferring
23 taxes on property under this section is void.
24 (m) Construction. – This section does not affect the attachment of a lien for personal
25 property taxes against a tax-deferred residence.
26 (n) Application. – An application for property tax relief provided by this section should
27 be filed during the regular listing period, but may be filed and must be accepted at any time up
28 to and through June 1 preceding the tax year for which the relief is claimed. Persons may apply
29 for this property tax relief by entering the appropriate information on a form made available by
30 the assessor under G.S. 105-282.1."
31 SECTION 1.(c) G.S. 105-282.1(a) is amended by adding a new subdivision to read:
32 "(3) Triennial application required. – An owner of a property eligible for the
33 property tax homestead circuit breaker under G.S. 105-277.1B must file an
34 application for the benefit to receive it. Once the application has been
35 approved, the owner is entitled to the benefit for the current tax year and the
36 two subsequent tax years thereafter unless the property loses its eligibility for
37 the benefit as a result of a disqualifying event under G.S. 105-277.1B(i)."
38 SECTION 1.(d) G.S. 105-277.1F(a)(2) is repealed.
39 SECTION 1.(e) G.S. 105-365.1(a)(3) is repealed.
40 SECTION 1.(f) G.S. 153A-148.1 reads as rewritten:
41 "§ 153A-148.1. Disclosure of certain information prohibited.
42 (a) Disclosure Prohibited. – Notwithstanding Chapter 132 of the General Statutes or any
43 other law regarding access to public records, local tax records that contain information about a
44 taxpayer's income or receipts are not public records. A current or former officer, employee, or
45 agent of a county who in the course of service to or employment by the county has access to
46 information about the amount of a taxpayer's income or receipts may not disclose the information
47 to any other person unless the disclosure is made for one of the following purposes:
48 …
49 (6) To include on a property tax receipt the amount of property taxes due and the
50 amount of property taxes deferred on a residence classified under
51 G.S. 105-277.1B, the property tax homestead circuit breaker.
